body:
@waltherg the commit reads "FIX: xxxx". It does not start with an imperative in addition it is too long (over 50 characters) and does not contain the Jira reference, a better message would be "[AIRFLOW-447] Store source URIs in Python 3 compatible list". 

Please _read_ the commit guidelines and see other PRs for examples, we use these messages to create a changelog on release. A proper formatted commit message is thus essential otherwise we have to do all that work at the end.

Furthermore can you do an empty commit to trigger the build again? I would like to see the tests pass before merging.

@plypaul 
One question. If most folks have one dag per file, is scheduling potentially slower? I will say that running the sequential executor with the new scheduler does not appear to work after say 5-10 minutes. It seems to get into a state where nothing gets scheduled.

Pull the latest code and unpause (or enable) 7+ examples. You will see it work for a short while and then nothing gets scheduled anymore. It works fine with LocalExecutor (and I suspect Celery, since you folks are running that).

@bolkedebruin thank you for elaborating - you are correct I had not fully read the contribution guidelines. Apologies for that.

I hope the new PR I opened over here will work:

https://github.com/apache/incubator-airflow/pull/1754

@gjreda As @bolkedebruin mentioned, you need to follow instructions on https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/AIRFLOW/Contributors%27+Guide

This means creating a JIRA, prefacing your PR and commit with the id and adding a link here to the JIRA, etc.... Please look at other PRs to follow as an example. 

Also, if you find other sure inconsistencies in the docs, feel free to include all of them in this PR. That will get it merged with greater expediency.

@msumit thank you for your feedback. Commit message is updated according to the rules.

@criccomini I am sorry for taking so long to respond. You have a good point, sometimes response status can be useful. The assumption of the current implementation is to keep it simple. Storing response text can go a long way and cover many use cases. Users have the ultimate knowledge of the response they expect. It can be parsed as JSON, XML or HTML later on.

Just like `BashOperator` stores the output of the command only, so does the current implementation of `HttpOperator`. Users can extend `HttpOperator` to xcom push more attributes of the response specific for their use case, just like they can extend `BashOperator` to push exit code of the shell command.

@plypaul Thanks. Unfortunately there seem to be more issues. There is quantitatively a large delay in tasks getting "run". I can reproduce the behavior quite easily and we have several reports (mailinglist, gitter) where people think tasks are not getting scheduled at all. Hopefully we can spend a little bit of time on this before your holiday so either we fix it before or I can help fixing it (by knowing where to look) .

(Tested on LovalExecutor btw)

Also: @r39132 @jlowin @mistercrunch
